<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-export SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/evernote-export4.dtd">
<en-export export-date="20260611T074028Z" application="Evernote" version="11.9.1">
  <note>
    <title>00. TB AR GMS PAS, W-S</title>
    <created>20140624T100312Z</created>
    <updated>20251020T081025Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><h3 style="--en-isCollapsed:false; --en-nodeId:101bc0a8-f8e9-4bee-9cea-d28d57877411;"><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Necrotizing granulomatous inflammation.</span></h3><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Sections show a granuloma with central caseating necrosis, surrounded by multinucleated giant cells, histiocytes and lymphoplasmacytic infiltration. No fungus is identified by stainings for GMS and PAS. Although no mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast stain and Auramine-Rhodamine stain, mycobaterial infection is highly suspected.</span></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">是TB</span></span></div><h3 style="--en-isCollapsed:false; --en-nodeId:4cbc4fa2-9265-48be-ae73-35f69e5751b4;"><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Necrotizing granulomatous inflammation with mycobacterial infection.</span></h3><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">Sections show __ tissue exhibiting prominent granulomatous inflammation featuring central caseating necrosis, surrounded by multinucleated giant cells, histiocytes and lymphoplasmacytic infiltration as well as scattered neutrophils. Mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast and Auramine-Rhodamine stains. No fungus is identified by stainings for GMS and PAS.</span></div><hr/><div><b><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="color:rgb(28, 51, 135);">No mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast stain. No fungus is identified by PAS.</span></span></span></b></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 9pt;"><span style="color:rgb(34, 34, 34);">No invasive carcinoma is demonstrated by AE1/AE3.     </span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">No mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast and Auramine-Rhodamine stains.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">No mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by</span></span> <span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">acid fast stain or TB immunostain. </span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">No fungus is identified by GMS and PAS.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-size: 12px;"> The GMS and PAS stains are negative for fungal organism.</span></div><div style="padding-left:40px;"><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">No fungus is identified by stainings for GMS and PAS.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div>No viral inclusion is demonstrated by anti-CMV immunostain. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color:rgb(188, 0, 88);">Although</span></span> <span style="font-size: 12px;">no mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast stain. Mycobaterial infection cannot be excluded. </span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Dr曾:  No mycobacterial microorganisms are identified by acid fast stain or Auramine-Rhodamine stain, nor is fungus identified with GM stain.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Stainings for GMS and PAS highlight the fungal hyphae and spores.</span></span></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>A small leiomyoma is identified in adjacent pulmonary</title>
    <created>20251023T073737Z</created>
    <updated>20251023T073745Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>A small leiomyoma is identified in adjacent pulmonary</div><div>  parenchyma, which is composed of bland spindle</div><div>  cells with an extremely low cellularity, with</div><div>  lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate at the periphery.</div><div>  By immunohistochemistry, the spindle cells are positive</div><div>  for desmin, H-caldesmon but not CD34 and HMB45. ER and PR </div><div>  show few positive cells with weak staining. </div><div>  Comment: This finding is most consistent with a leiomyoma.</div><div>  However, correlation with the patient's clinical history,</div><div>  including any prior surgical resection of uterine</div><div>  leiomyomas, is recommended to exclude the possibility of</div><div>  benign metastasizing leiomyoma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Abscess, LUNG</title>
    <created>20180213T042229Z</created>
    <updated>20230829T023708Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br clear="none" /></div><div style="margin-top: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;">Abscess.</div><div style="margin-top: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;">Microscopic description:<br/></div><div><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">The lung tissue shows extensive necrosis with mixed inflammatory cells infiltration and foci of abscess formation. No evidence of</span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif; text-decoration: underline;">granuloma</span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: gotham, helvetica, sans-serif;">or malignancy is observed.</span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Acute and chronic bronchiolitis</title>
    <created>20180808T062121Z</created>
    <updated>20180808T062452Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Acute and chronic bronchiolitis</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show peribronchiolar infiltration of mixed</div><div>inflammatory cells, accompanied by intraluminal collections</div><div>of neutrophils as well as mucus. Mild fibrosis is seen.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ADENOCA (should r/o meta)</title>
    <created>20230807T043929Z</created>
    <updated>20260326T081205Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Adenocarcinoma. see Comment.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows lung tissue infiltrated by neoplastic columnar</div><div>cells with pleomorphic nuclei arranged in glandular pattern</div><div>and in small clusters.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells are positive for CK7,</div><div>CK20, CDX2 but not TTF-1, Napsin A, GATA3, and PAX8.</div><div><br/></div><div>Comment:</div><div>Metastases must be ruled out first, particularly from the</div><div>gastrointestinal system, before rendering a diagnosis of</div><div>primary pulmonary enteric-type adenocarcinoma.</div><hr/><div>Adenocarcinoma; metastasis from colorectal primary should be</div><div>excluded. See comment.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic Findings:</div><div>Section shows infiltrative tubuloglandular structures lined</div><div>by neoplastic columnar cells with necrosis in a</div><div>desmoplastic stroma.</div><div><br/></div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the tumor cells are positive for</div><div>CK20 and CDX-2, and negative for TTF-1, CK7, and p40.</div><div><br/></div><div>COMMENT: Metastasis, particularly from the lower</div><div>gastrointestinal tract, should first be ruled out; in the</div><div>absence of such findings, primary pulmonary enteric-type</div><div>adenocarcinoma may be considered.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ADENOCA invasive mucinous type, LUNG, biopsy</title>
    <created>20170321T234416Z</created>
    <updated>20230907T024052Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Invasive mucinous adenocarcinoma</div><div><br/></div><div>Section shows lung tissue infiltrated by columnar cells with abundant intracytoplasmic mucin and basally oriented nuclei, arranged in acinar pattern.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells express CK7 and CK20 but not TTF-1. The overall features can be consistent with a primary pulmonary invasive mucinous adenocarcinoma. Clinical and radiological correlation should be made to exclude metastasis.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ADENOCA, LUNG, BIOPSY</title>
    <created>20170206T074532Z</created>
    <updated>20241210T045641Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="margin-top:16px;"><span style="font-family: gotham;">Adenocarcinoma.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">The section shows lung tissue infiltrated by large cells with pleomorphic nuclei and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm with ____ patterns.</span></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells express TTF-1, confirming the diagnosis of adenocarcinoma.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: gotham;">(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</span></div><div><br/></div><div style="margin-bottom:16px;"><span style="font-family: gotham;">Complex glands</span> </div><div style="margin-bottom:16px;"><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="color:rgb(252, 18, 51);">NOTE: The specimen is not adequate for molecular testing. </span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>ADENOCA, mucinous with lepidic pattern, LUNG, BIOPSY</title>
    <created>20170321T234445Z</created>
    <updated>20230907T024100Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Mucinous adenocarcinoma with lepidic pattern</div><div><br/></div><div>Section shows lung tissue infiltrated by columnar cells with abundant intracytoplasmic mucin and basally oriented nuclei, arranged in lepidic pattern.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the tumor cells express CK7 and CK20 but not TTF-1. The overall features can be consistent with a primary pulmonary invasive mucinous adenocarcinoma. Clinical and radiological correlation should be made to exclude metastasis.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>AIS</title>
    <created>20210525T061050Z</created>
    <updated>20260313T044822Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Adenocarcinoma in situ.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections taken from two tumors show atypical pneumocyte proliferation without invasive growth.</div><div><br/></div><hr/><div><br/></div><div>adenocarcinoma in situ.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections taken from nodule show a subpleural tumor</div><div>   composed of atypical pneumocyte proliferation in purely</div><div>   lepidic pattern without invasive growth. The size is __</div><div>   mm. The surgical margin is free of tumor.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Anthracosis (LN)</title>
