    <updated>20250702T014038Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Anthracosis with granuloma like aggregates of </div><div>  histiocytes and nodal hyaline scars is noted.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Aortic dissection 2014111730, 2014122706, 2015010808</title>
    <created>20170215T083113Z</created>
    <updated>20191101T061046Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: Gulim;">consistent with aortic dissection.</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Gulim;"><br/></span></div><div><span style="font-family: Gulim;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Gulim;">Section shows blood and fibrin clots within the splitted aortic wall, which reveals myxoid degeneration. There is no evidence of malignancy.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>apical cap</title>
    <created>20190624T064306Z</created>
    <updated>20231205T023249Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>apical cap</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections taken from the nodule show subpleural</div><div>fibrosis which features an admixture of eosinophilic</div><div>mature collagen and basophilic elastin fiber. The elastin</div><div>fiber is highlighted by EVG stain. No invasive carcinoma is</div><div>demonstrated by AE1/AE3. Staining for HMB45 is negative.</div><div>CD31 shows no vascular lesion. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>atheroma</title>
    <created>20191211T075230Z</created>
    <updated>20240411T065138Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Coronary artery, endarterectomy ---</div><div>Consistent with atheroma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Gross description:</div><div>The specimen consists of _ pieces of tissue up to __ cm.</div><div>All for section (decal).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows atherosclerotic plaque with a few inflammatory</div><div>cells (lymphocytes) scattered within the atheroma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>atherosclerosis</title>
    <created>20200819T042126Z</created>
    <updated>20200819T042353Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Ascending aorta, repair --- atherosclerosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows aorta with atherosclerotic plaque admixed with</div><div>some lymphocytes, and foam cells scattered within the</div><div>atheroma. Cholesterol crystals and cell debris are seen.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Atypical adenomatous hyperplasia, AAH</title>
    <created>20161129T070132Z</created>
    <updated>20210525T061129Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Atypical adenomatous hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows lung tissue cores with mildly enlarged and hyperchromatic of alveolar lining cells.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Atypical cells (biopsy)</title>
    <created>20170117T012450Z</created>
    <updated>20170117T012520Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows bronchoalveolar tissue focally revealing enlargement and hyperchromatism of alveolar lining cells, which can be reactive or neoplastic. Aggregates of foamy histiocytes are seen focally in the alveolar space. Although these atypical cells are </div><div>imunopositive for TTF-1, the finding is not reliable to confirm a cancerous lesion in this situation. Together with image finding, re-biopsy is mandatory to reach a firm diagnosis. </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Bronchiolar smooth muscle hyperplasia</title>
    <created>20240402T043535Z</created>
    <updated>20250506T024525Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Bronchiolar smooth muscle hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows thickening ot the smooth muscle around bronchiole.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Carcinoid tumorlets</title>
    <created>20170317T031345Z</created>
    <updated>20231103T074032Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Carcinoid tumorlets</div><div><br/></div><div>_ foci of carcinoid tumorlets are seen on section _, measuring up to _ mm at greatest dimension. It is characterized by proliferation of spindle cells revealing finely stippled chromatin and inconspicuous nucleoli. Mitosis is</div><div>hardly identified. </div><div><br/></div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the carcinoid tumorlets are immunoreactive to CD56, chromogranin A and synaptophysin.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Chronic inflammation, bronchus</title>
    <created>20161212T065954Z</created>
    <updated>20161212T070040Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows bronchoalveolar/ bronchial tissue with chronic inflammatory cells infiltrate in subepithelial region. Neither granuloma nor malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Cryptococcosis</title>
    <created>20161220T084550Z</created>
    <updated>20190604T031205Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source-url>https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1C1BEMX_zh-TWTW773TW773&amp;q=Cryptococcus+infection&amp;spell=1&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwiXq5Gq7c7iAhUFULwKHTKLAAAQBQgqKAA&amp;biw=780&amp;bih=357</source-url>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Cryptococcal Infection.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The section shows lung tissue cores infiltrated by chronic inflammatory cells and rounded fungal microorganism forming small groups in clear gelatinous capsule, as highlighted by PAS and GMS staining. The overall pictures are compatible with<br/></div><div>cryptococcal infection. There is no evidence of malignancy.</div><div><br/></div><div>SPECILA STAINING: GMS and PAS stains.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
